Yesterday, I had a dream that I was in a waterpark… swarming with half-human, half-seafood creatures, while being chased down slippery slides and across an ocean that felt like hardened jelly by a turtle-dentist wielding jagged scissors. He kept shouting questions about the cleanliness of my enamel, and instead of being fazed by this, I kept laughing and throwing – um – loofahs? at him. And somehow, all of this made *perfect* sense to me while I was asleep.

If you’re wondering how I remember all of this, I honestly don’t – I just remember bits and pieces that I scribbled onto a piece of paper when I woke up (keeping in mind the sanctity of this article), that have morphed into a kind of fuzzy memory in my head. I recall how I felt, though– something that, in hindsight, feels a bit more nightmarish (being chased by a scary turtle-dentist with a sharp object is a little worrisome) had felt like a jolly time in the dream, and weirdly– it felt like it was all *normal*. Apparently, somewhere in the depths of my subconscious, seafood waterparks for half-seafood humans are totally acceptable, and hard oceans filled with loofahs are just part of the scenery.

*My* question is: why do I dream about my crush one day, and a scary turtle-dentist the next? How can I keep dreaming about my crush? Why doesn’t my crush like me ba– okay, I might be getting a bit off-topic here.

But seriously, what’s up with this twisted dichotomy of dream logic? And why does my brain randomly decide to give me nightmares from time to time? What determines the subject or, even the genre of my dreams? What does it mean? Also, why can’t I remember anything afterwards? Why does it all make perfect sense while sleeping? How do dreams even *work*? *Why* *do they happen? Can I control my dream?*

If you accompany me in having any one of these bajillion questions, you’ve come to the right place. Let’s start off with the most basic one: what even *is* a dream? But first, please enjoy this random meme I found on the Internet.

# **What Even *Is* a Dream?** 

### 1\. Introduction: The Dreamworld Unveiled – why we dream, Sleep Stages and the Biochemistry of Dreaming

* Introduce the different stages of sleep (REM and non-REM), explaining how dreams are most vivid during REM sleep. Highlight the biochemistry behind each stage, and briefly set up how neurotransmitters like serotonin, dopamine, and acetylcholine play key roles in shaping our dreams.

The leading theories on why dreams happen, including:

* Memory consolidation

* Emotional processing

* Problem-solving

* Random neural firing (Activation-Synthesis Theory)

### 2\. The Biochemistry of Dreams: Neurotransmitters, Brain Activity, and Emotional Processing

* Dive deeper into how neurotransmitters influence dream formation, focusing on their role in memory consolidation, emotional regulation, and creativity. Discuss how the brain’s activity during sleep affects the content of dreams (e.g., the strange logic of dreams and the formation of emotions like fear or affection).

### 3\. Why Do Dreams Defy Logic? Emotional Free-For-Alls and the Role of the Prefrontal Cortex \+ why it all makes sense in the moment

* Explore the reduced activity of the prefrontal cortex during sleep and how this leads to the illogical, often absurd nature of dreams. Discuss how the limbic system governs emotional content, such as dreams about crushes or fear-driven nightmares.

### 4\. Nightmares and Contradictions: The Biochemical Basis of Stress, Fear, and Dream Genres \+ what ur dreams mean (biological and psychological perspective)

* Examine the neurochemistry behind nightmares, focusing on cortisol and stress hormones. Explain how the emotional state and brain chemistry influence the genre of dreams, whether they’re romantic, terrifying, or bizarre.

### 5\. Dream Recall: Why Do We Forget Most Dreams and How Does Memory Work in Sleep?

* Explain the memory consolidation process, including the role of the hippocampus, and why dream recall is often poor. Tie this into the biochemistry of sleep and memory retention.

### 6\. Can You Control Your Dreams? The Science of Lucid Dreaming and Dream Influence

* Introduce lucid dreaming, its biochemical mechanisms, and how certain neurotransmitters allow for conscious control over dreams. Discuss techniques for increasing lucidity and influencing dream content.

### 7\. Conclusion: The Neurochemistry Behind the Mystery of Dreams

* Summarize the key points about the biochemistry of dreaming, emphasizing how sleep stages, neurotransmitters, and brain regions shape the dream experience, from strange logic to emotional processing.

To dream or not to dream? That is NOT the question.
